    "author_association": "COLLABORATOR",
    "body": "@PaulHigin itâ€™s already documented, it states itâ€™s been SHA256 since PowerShell v3 but that is not the case.\r\n\r\nhttps://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/microsoft.powershell.security/set-authenticodesignature?view=powershell-7.2\r\n\r\n> For PowerShell 3.0, the default is SHA256, which is the Windows default hashing algorithm. For PowerShell 2.0, the default is SHA1\r\n\r\nWhile technically a breaking change I feel this should be back-ported as far as possible. SHA1 has been essentially unsupported for years now and PowerShell should be using SHA256 where possible.\n\n<blockquote><img src=\"https://docs.microsoft.com/media/logos/logo-powershell-social.png\" width=\"48\" align=\"right\"><div><strong><a href=\"https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/microsoft.powershell.security/set-authenticodesignature\">Set-AuthenticodeSignature (Microsoft.PowerShell.Security) - PowerShell</a></strong></div><div> This cmdlet is only available on the Windows platform.  The Set-AuthenticodeSignature cmdlet adds an Authenticode signature to any file that supports Subject Interface Package (SIP). In a PowerShell script file, the signature takes the form of a block of text that indicates the end of the instructions that are executed in the script. If there is a signature in the file when this cmdlet runs, that signature is removed. </div></blockquote>",
